A new study by the United Nations suggests that 463 million children, over one-third of all school-children in the world, do not have access to virtual education as a result of factors such as lack of equipment or the lack of remote educational facilities. Additionally, the UN estimated that over 1.5 billion children in the entire world have been affected by lock-downs imposed to contain the coronavirus pandemic, and warned that the situation may yet grow worse. 

The report read, "The sheer number of children whose education was completely disrupted for months on end is a global education emergency. The repercussions could be felt in economies and societies for decades to come". 

Additionally, massive disparities were observed in terms of regions, with 121 million children coming from Sub-Saharan Africa and 147 million from Sub-Saharan Africa. Rural areas particularly were found to suffer especially due to lack of internet access and other online learning facilities. 

The study involved the usage of globally representative data obtained from 100 countries on the availability and presence and availability of technology which can enable online learning, such as television, radio and internet in households.

Under the firm watch of #NewDelhi’s #Mayur Vihar #metrostation a narrow, dusty road swirls its way to the village of #Yamuna Khadar. Amidst the perpetual din of #constructionworkers mainly #migrants living in make-shift huts, a #coaching centre has been functioning for last 5 years in a road-side shack. “When I first started teaching, students didn’t know the basics of #mathematics & #science,” says Panna Lal, 22, a teacher at the centre since 2015. Although students would go to a nearby #governmentschool, most of them failed in ninth grade and dropped out.

Since most families in the village comprise tenant #farmers who work on rented land, children are under pressure to forego studies & join their parents. It is this problem that Lal set out to address. The centre takes a minimal fee of INR 100 per month from kids in lower classes & INR 250 from kids in higher classes.

The #lockdown of about five months due to ongoing #Covid19pandemic has disrupted regular #studies for students at the centre. “Most of the students have forgotten all that they learnt & many still fear coming to school,” explains Dev Kumar, another teacher.

However, due to closure of #schools and the break in studies due to absence of #digitaldevices the number of students coming here has jumped manifold. While before the #pandemic, there were 300 students in two centres, the institute has added five more centres with another 550 students, making it a total of 750 in seven centres.

“Most of them don’t even have an #Aadharcard and get no #government benefits in ration or shelter. They also don’t have any #publichospitals nearby. Their make shift huts have no electricity or portable water,” Kumar adds.

The land on which the school stands belongs to the #delhidevelopmentauthority. Even though people like Lal & Kumar are trying to #educatethecommunity, lack of any #governmentsupport and absence of #basicutilities like #electricity & water has kept residents of Yamuna Khadar in substandard lives & without hopes.

node.text:
Kenapa sih sebelum memulai bisnis, Kamu perlu memikirkan target market secara rinci dan matang?

Sederhananya, Kamu tidak akan menjual produk tanpa tahu kepada siapa Kamu akan menjualnya bukan? Oleh karenanya target market menjadi satu bagian yang fundamental sebelum Kamu memulai bisnis.

Target market lah yang nantinya akan menentukan strategi marketing apa yang Kamu lakukan dan peluang apa yang bisa membuat bisnismu berkembang di masa yang akan datang.

Nah dalam menetapkan target market ini, Kamu bisa melakukan segmentasi pasar terlebih dahulu, dengan cara mengelompokkan konsumen yang memiliki kesamaan interest atau ketertarikan, sebab Kamu tidak mungkin bisa melayani semua kebutuhan dan keinginan konsumen yang heterogen.

Finished my first pandemic journal. 164 pages; 57 drawings; a chronicle of 167 days of the most unusual times we have ever lived. Pandemic; economic collapse; racial strife - these are the times we have only read about until now. This journal was my accounting of our family’s life in lockdown and beyond. We are ridiculously fortunate to live this version of events. So this journal is a humble marker of time with family in the midst of catharsis. This was my mental solace in 167 days of unrelenting turmoil. It was my mental processing plant; a talisman; a repository of swirling emotions and an effort to stave off the blurring of days during confinement. This was how I made sense of this crazy version of life.
Today I start the next one. Who knows what fresh drama will unfold this fall? It’s going to be big. 
.

Members of the Indian Gym’s Welfare Federation gathered near Safdarjung Airport Friday morning to protest against the Delhi government and L-G Anil Baijal for not allowing gyms and fitness centres to reopen in the capital.

Federation president Sunil Kumar Tonk said, “While gyms in the neighbouring towns, including Noida, Gurgaon and Faridabad, have opened up, lakhs of people employed in Delhi gyms are suffering. There are many who have to borrow from friends to run their houses. It has been more than six months that gyms have been shut. If all other places, including restaurants and salons, can open, why are they not allowing gyms to be opened? "

"We are ready with all precautions. It is a loss of livelihood for lakhs of people, the government must wake up now,” he said .

Via - ThePrint

What are coronaviruses?ü¶†üåé

Coronavirus

A family of viruses, seven of which are known to infect people. They get their name from the crown-like spikes—coronas—that appear on the viruses under a microscope. Coronaviruses can cause the common cold (which can also be caused by other viruses, such as rhinoviruses), as well as dangerous illnesses such as severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) and Middle East respiratory syndrome (MERS). SARS CoV-2, the coronavirus virus first discovered in December 2019, causes the disease now known as COVID-19.

SARS (Severe acute respiratory syndrome)

A coronavirus, which first infected humans in 2002, that reached epidemic proportions before it was contained—there have been no outbreaks since 2003. SARS causes fever, headache, body aches, a dry cough, hypoxia (oxygen deficiency), and usually pneumonia. SARS and SARS CoV-2 are related genetically, but the diseases they cause are different.

SARS-CoV-2 (Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2)

The new coronavirus that causes COVID-19, which is believed to have started in animals and spread to humans. Animal-to-person spread was suspected after the initial outbreak in December among people who had a link to a large seafood and live animal market in Wuhan, China. While no one knows for sure how SARS-CoV-2 spread from an animal (and what type of animal) to a human, SARS-CoV-2 is a betacoronavirus, which means it originated in bats. 

COVID-19 (Coronavirus Disease 2019)

Just as the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) causes acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (AIDS), the coronavirus SARS-CoV-2 causes COVID-19. The symptoms of COVID-19 include cough, fever, and shortness of breath. While the disease appears to cause mild to moderate illness in most people, in others it has caused life-threatening pneumonia and death. Doctors and researchers continue to learn more about the disease, so information about symptoms, prevention, and treatment may change as more data becomes available.

Discipline
BY GEORGE HERBERT
Throw away thy rod,
Throw away thy wrath:
 O my God,
Take the gentle path.

For my heart’s desire
Unto thine is bent:
 I aspire
To a full consent.

Not a word or look
I affect to own,
 But by book,
And thy book alone.

Though I fail, I weep:
Though I halt in pace,
 Yet I creep
To the throne of grace.

Then let wrath remove;
Love will do the deed:
 For with love
Stony hearts will bleed.

Love is swift of foot;
Love’s a man of war,
 And can shoot,
And can hit from far.

Who can ’scape his bow?
That which wrought on thee,
 Brought thee low,
Needs must work on me.

Throw away thy rod;
Though man frailties hath,
 Thou art God:
Throw away thy wrath.
